.
 In addition to the cost of lives, the economic impact of cancer is also
 staggering.
 It is estimated that the the premature deaths and disabilities caused by
 the disease costs more than 900 billion US dollars each year, which is
 more than 1.5% of the global gross domestic product, without accounting
 the direct medical expenses 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "AmericanCancerSociety2010"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This disease is characterized by uncontrolled cellular reproduction.
 It is caused by multiple internal and external factors --some of which
 are known and others remain unknown-- that affect cellular self-control
 mechanisms.
 When cancerous cells appear, they grow and reproduce without control leading
 to the formation of tumors that may affect an organ or organism by causing
 sickness, loss of sensation or cognitive abilities, pain, organ malfunction,
 and sometimes death 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "National2009"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Breast cancer is the leading type among all cancers.
 It is one of the most frequent, and the one with the highest absolute mortality
 in the world.
 In 2012, 1.7 million new cases were reported worldwide, accounting for 26%
 of all cancers in women excluding non-melanoma skin cancer.
 Global mortality was estimated above 500 thousand deaths, representing
 14% of all cancer-related deaths in women 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ferlay2013"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The causes of breast cancer are not completely identified.
 Different studies have associated genetic, environmental and behavioral
 factors with the disease 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Knaul2009"

\end_inset

.
 Given the complexity of the disease, it is difficult to detect or treat
 in a generalized way, and requires costly efforts to provide early detection
 and personalized treatment.
 In general, it is widely accepted that early detection of breast cancer
 decreases its mortality 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ng2003,JinshanTang2009"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Breast cancer is an heterogeneous disease in various levels.
 There are different types of breast cancer based on the structure where
 it originated: ductal and lobular are the most common.
 Each type has a variety of characteristics and symptoms that may or not
 be present, which sometimes decrease the chance of detecting the cancer
 in an early stage.
 Furthermore, at a genetic level, there are molecular cancer subtypes which
 can also determine the course of the disease and its response to treatment.
